properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong comeback of humidity beginning on Sunday. The heat will persist through Tuesday. The hottest days will be Monday and Tuesday with humidex values near 40. Drink 6 to 8 glasses of water per day. Follow your physician's instructions regarding the amount of fluid to drink; Limit physical activities; Reduce health risks to young children by cooling them often, hydrating them adequately and reducing their exposure to heat. Plan to visit and check up on loved ones (neighbours, friends and family), especially those who suffer from a loss of autonomy or from a chronic disease, or those who live alone, in order to ensure they are cool and not dehydrated. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Hot and humid conditions continue this weekend into early next week. Daytime maximum temperatures of 31 degrees are expected along with overnight low temperatures of 20 degrees. properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of severe thunderstorms that may be capable of producing strong wind gusts, large hail and heavy rain. Scattered thunderstorms are expected to track into Saskatchewan from Alberta this evening along a cold front. Some of these thunderstorms may reach severe thresholds. This severe thunderstorm watch may be expanded eastwards as the evening progresses. ### Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Humidex values reaching 35 are expected for the next 2 days. A warm and increasingly humid air mass will remain over the Maritimes into the middle of next week. Nighttime low temperatures are not expected to drop below 18 C tonight and inland temperatures near 28 C are forecast for Sunday. After Sunday, the warm and humid conditions may persist into the middle of the coming week. Conditions could be slightly cooler on Monday, with temperatures likely falling to 26 to 28 degrees. properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of severe thunderstorms that may be capable of producing strong wind gusts, large hail and heavy rain. Scattered thunderstorms are tracking across portions of western and central Saskatchewan this evening along a cold front. Some of these thunderstorms may reach severe thresholds. This watch may be expanded to regions northeastward throughout the night. ### Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Temperatures reaching 30 degrees Celsius combined with overnight lows near 18 degrees Celsius are expected for the next 3 to 5 days. A warm and increasingly humid air mass will remain over the Maritimes into the middle of next week. Maximum daytime temperatures on Sunday are expected to reach or exceed 30 C across southern and eastern New Brunswick, although coastal areas may remain somewhat cooler in onshore breezes. Maximum humidex values are expected to be near or slightly below 35 on Sunday. Minimum temperatures tonight are forecast to be near 19 C, which will not provide much relief from the heat. It is likely that the heat will continue into the middle of next week. Humidity is expected to increase on Tuesday and Wednesday, when humidex values could exceed 36. ### Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Temperatures reaching 29 degrees Celsius combined with overnight lows near 16 degrees Celsius are expected for the next 5 days. A warm and increasingly humid air mass will remain over the Maritimes into the middle of next week. Maximum temperatures on Sunday are expected to reach or exceed 29 C, especially in the valley and interior regions of southwestern Nova Scotia. Maximum humidex values are not expected to exceed 35 for the remainder of the weekend. Low temperatures tonight are forecast to remain above 15 C, although low lying areas may be cooler. It is likely that the heat will spread further to the east on Sunday and continue into the middle of next week, as humidity continues to increase. Humidex values could exceed 36 on Tuesday and Wednesday. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Watch for the effects of heat illness: swelling, rash, cramps, fainting, heat exhaustion, heat stroke and the worsening of some health conditions. Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Information is provided on the Nova Scotia Department of Health and Wellness website at https://novascotia.ca/heat-related-illness/. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
